From: Bob Van Valzah <bob@vanvalzah.com>
Subject: [PATCH v2] igc: hold tmreg_lock in adjfine to serialize TIMINCA writes

igc_ptp_adjfine_i225() writes IGC_TIMINCA without holding any lock.
Every other PTP clock operation in igc_ptp.c (adjtime, gettime, settime)
holds tmreg_lock when accessing timing registers, but adjfine does not.

When ptp4l (or any PTP stack) sends hardware-timestamped packets while
a clock discipline daemon adjusts the frequency, the unsynchronized
TIMINCA write can race with the hardware's TX timestamp capture,
producing a corrupt timestamp.  After IGC_PTP_TX_TIMEOUT (15s), the
driver logs "Tx timestamp timeout" and eventually the EXTTS subsystem
stops delivering PPS events.

Reproducible: one thread calling clock_adjtime(ADJ_FREQUENCY) at
~200k/s while another sends hardware-timestamped UDP packets triggers
the timeout within 17 seconds.

Fix: hold tmreg_lock around the TIMINCA write, consistent with how
all other timing register accesses are protected.

v2: Use tmreg_lock (timing register lock) instead of ptp_tx_lock
    (TX timestamp queue lock) per maintainer feedback.  Drop the
    TX-pending check and -EBUSY return — tmreg_lock serializes the
    register write itself, which is sufficient.

Signed-off-by: Bob Van Valzah <bob@vanvalzah.com>
---
 drivers/net/ethernet/intel/igc/igc_ptp.c | 5 ++++-
 1 file changed, 4 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/igc/igc_ptp.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/igc/igc_ptp.c
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/igc/igc_ptp.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/igc/igc_ptp.c
@@ -47,6 +47,7 @@ static int igc_ptp_adjfine_i225(struct ptp_clock_info *ptp, long scaled_ppm)
 {
 	struct igc_adapter *igc = container_of(ptp, struct igc_adapter,
 					       ptp_caps);
 	struct igc_hw *hw = &igc->hw;
+	unsigned long flags;
 	int neg_adj = 0;
 	u64 rate;
 	u32 inca;
@@ -63,7 +64,9 @@ static int igc_ptp_adjfine_i225(struct ptp_clock_info *ptp, long scaled_ppm)
 	if (neg_adj)
 		inca |= ISGN;

-	wr32(IGC_TIMINCA, inca);
+	spin_lock_irqsave(&igc->tmreg_lock, flags);
+	wr32(IGC_TIMINCA, inca);
+	spin_unlock_irqrestore(&igc->tmreg_lock, flags);

 	return 0;
 }
